<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Distribution of S. cordatum." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.198.79514.figure15" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/689708" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">15</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Solanum cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs from northeastern Africa and the Arabian Peninsula to Pakistan and western India (Punjab, Gujarat, Maharashtra). The record of 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Tamil Nadu (
<bibRefCitation author="Ramachandran, A" journalOrPublisher="Rheedea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="56 - 58" refId="B202" refString="Ramachandran, A, Viswanathan, MB, 2010. Solanum cordatum (Solanaceae) - a new record to southern India. Rheedea 20: 56 - 58" title="Solanum cordatum (Solanaceae) - a new record to southern India." volume="20" year="2010">Ramachandran and Viswanathan 2010</bibRefCitation>
) is based on mis-identified specimens of 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. wightii" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="wightii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. wightii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Solanum cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in grassland, bushland, and open woodland on silty, sandy, or stony soil; low elevations (not recorded for India, from sea level to 1,500 m fide 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF03027161" author="Vorontsova, MS" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 428" refId="B259" refString="Vorontsova, MS, Knapp, S, 2016. A revision of the &quot;spiny solanums,&quot; Solanum subgenus Leptostemonum (Solanaceae), in Africa and Madagascar. Systematic Botany Monographs 99: 1 - 428, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF03027161" title="A revision of the &quot; spiny solanums, &quot; Solanum subgenus Leptostemonum (Solanaceae), in Africa and Madagascar." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF03027161" volume="99" year="2016">Vorontsova and Knapp 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="common names and uses">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Common names and uses.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
None recorded from the region (see 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF03027161" author="Vorontsova, MS" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 428" refId="B259" refString="Vorontsova, MS, Knapp, S, 2016. A revision of the &quot;spiny solanums,&quot; Solanum subgenus Leptostemonum (Solanaceae), in Africa and Madagascar. Systematic Botany Monographs 99: 1 - 428, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF03027161" title="A revision of the &quot; spiny solanums, &quot; Solanum subgenus Leptostemonum (Solanaceae), in Africa and Madagascar." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF03027161" volume="99" year="2016">Vorontsova and Knapp 2016</bibRefCitation>
for Africa).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Conservation status</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2021-1.RLTS.T186619213A186619254.en" author="Knapp, S" journalOrPublisher="Anales del Jardin Botanico de Madrid" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B125" refString="Knapp, S, 2021a. Solanum cordatum. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2021: e.T186619213A186619254. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2021-1.RLTS.T186619213A186619254.en" title="Solanum cordatum. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2021: e. T 186619213 A 186619254." url="https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2021-1.RLTS.T186619213A186619254.en" year="2021 a">Knapp 2021a</bibRefCitation>
).
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Solanum cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been formally assessed as a species of Least Concern (LC; https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/186619213/186619254).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Solanum cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be much less commonly collected in western India than is the very similar and sympatric 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. forskalii" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="forskalii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. forskalii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. forskalii" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="forskalii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. forskalii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its compact multangulate stem pubescence of trichomes with many very short (&lt;0.1 mm long) rays, 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. forskalii" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="forskalii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. forskalii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has porrect-stellate trichomes with fewer rays that are marginally longer (&gt; 0.15 mm long); stems of 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appear white dotted from the stubby trichomes. Leaf petioles of 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are decurrent and narrowly winged, while leaves of 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. forskalii" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="forskalii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. forskalii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distinctly petiolate. The calyx lobes of 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are longer and narrower than those of 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. forskalii" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="forskalii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. forskalii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, while anthers are shorter in 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(3-5 mm versus 4.5-7 mm).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
In eastern Africa, 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is deciduous in the dry season, growing opportunistically during times of moisture (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF03027161" author="Vorontsova, MS" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 428" refId="B259" refString="Vorontsova, MS, Knapp, S, 2016. A revision of the &quot;spiny solanums,&quot; Solanum subgenus Leptostemonum (Solanaceae), in Africa and Madagascar. Systematic Botany Monographs 99: 1 - 428, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF03027161" title="A revision of the &quot; spiny solanums, &quot; Solanum subgenus Leptostemonum (Solanaceae), in Africa and Madagascar." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF03027161" volume="99" year="2016">Vorontsova and Knapp 2016</bibRefCitation>
). This may be part of the reason for its relatively fewer collections in India than 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. forskalii" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="forskalii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. forskalii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; this species has more robust leaves that are not deciduous. 
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, JRI" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B273" refString="Wood, JRI, 1997. A handbook of the Yemen flora. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew." title="A handbook of the Yemen flora. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew." year="1997">Wood (1997)</bibRefCitation>
suggested that 
<taxonomicName family="Solanaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. cordatum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="cordatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. cordatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was an &quot;Indian species which extends west to Yemen but is only found in Africa in Somalia.&quot; It is indeed found only in the Horn of Africa (Somalia, Ethiopia, and northern Kenya).
</paragraph>
